# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: radare2-analysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] A **debugger** is software for executing a computer program in an environment that allows for programming-level inspection and control.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] A debugger is often used to debug, but can be used for other goals including testing.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Common features of a debugger include stepping through code line-by-line, breaking into the program's flow of control, managing breakpoints, and reporting and modifying memory.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] **symbolic debugger**) provides a user experience that integrates the program's source code.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Typically, such a debugger can indicate which line of source code corresponds to the execution point of the program and allows for reading and writing memory via the symbols of the source code.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] In contrast, a **low-level debugger** (a.k.a.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] **machine-language debugger**) shows the execution point as machine code or its associated assembly language and allows memory access by address only.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Some debuggers offer two modes of operation, full or partial simulation, to limit this impact.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Typically, debuggers offer a query processor, a symbol resolver, an expression interpreter, and a debug support interface at its top level.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] It may also be possible to continue execution at a different location in the program to bypass a crash or logical error.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] The same functionality which makes a debugger useful for correcting bugs allows it to be used as a software cracking tool to evade copy protection, digital rights management, and other software protection features.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] It often also makes it useful as a general verification tool, fault coverage, and performance analyser, especially if instruction path lengths are shown.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Most mainstream debugging engines, such as gdb and dbx, provide console-based command line interfaces.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Debugger front-ends are popular extensions to debugger engines that provide IDE integration, program animation, and visualization features.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] If a program is running with a debugger, and an exception occurs because of a programming bug or invalid data, the debugger is notified of the exception.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] When the program "traps" or reaches a preset condition, the debugger typically shows the location in the original code if it is a source-level debugger or symbolic debugger.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] If it is a low-level debugger or a machine-language debugger it shows the line in the disassembly (unless it also has online access to the original source code and can display the appropriate section of code from the assembly or compilation).
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Record and replay debugging, also known as "software flight recording" or "program execution recording", captures application state changes and stores them to disk as each instruction in a program executes.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] The recording can then be replayed and interactively debugged to diagnose and resolve defects.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Record and replay debugging is useful for remote debugging and for resolving intermittent, non-deterministic, and other hard-to-reproduce defects.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Some debuggers include a feature called "**reverse debugging**", also known as "historical debugging" or "backwards debugging".
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] These debuggers make it possible to step a program's execution backwards in time.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Microsoft Visual Studio (2010 Ultimate edition, 2012 Ultimate, 2013 Ultimate, and 2015 Enterprise edition) offers IntelliTrace reverse debugging for C#, Visual Basic .NET, and some other languages, but not C++.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Reverse debuggers also exist for C, C++, Java, Python, Perl, and other languages.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Some are open source; some are proprietary commercial software.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Some reverse debuggers slow down the target by orders of magnitude, but the best reverse debuggers cause a slowdown of 2× or less.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Reverse debugging is very useful for certain types of problems, but is not commonly used.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] In addition to the features of reverse debuggers, time travel debugging also allow users to interact with the program, changing the history if desired, and watch how the program responds.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Some debuggers operate on a single specific language while others can handle multiple languages transparently.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] For example, if the main target program is written in COBOL but calls assembly language subroutines and PL/1 subroutines, the debugger may have to dynamically switch modes to accommodate the changes in language as they occur.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Some debuggers also incorporate memory protection to avoid storage violations such as buffer overflow.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] This may be extremely important in transaction processing environments where memory is dynamically allocated from memory 'pools' on a task by task basis.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Some processors have hardware support for single-stepping a program, such as the trap flag.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Some of the most capable and popular debuggers implement only a simple command line interface (CLI)—often to maximize portability and minimize resource consumption.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Developers typically consider debugging via a graphical user interface (GUI) easier and more productive.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] This is the reason for visual front-ends, that allow users to monitor and control subservient CLI-only debuggers via graphical user interface.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Some GUI debugger front-ends are designed to be compatible with a variety of CLI-only debuggers, while others are targeted at one specific debugger.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Debugging is often used to illegally crack or pirate software, which is usually illegal even when done non-maliciously.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] Crackme's are programs specifically designed to be cracked or debugged.
[src:radare2-analysis/debugger] These programs allow those with debuggers to practice their debugging ability without getting into legal trouble.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] A **disassembler** is a computer program that translates machine language into assembly language—the inverse operation to that of an assembler.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] The output of disassembly is typically formatted for human-readability rather than for input to an assembler, making disassemblers primarily a reverse-engineering tool.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] Common uses include analyzing the output of high-level programming language compilers and their optimizations, recovering source code when the original is lost, performing malware analysis, modifying software (such as binary patching), and software cracking.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] A disassembler differs from a decompiler, which targets a high-level language rather than an assembly language.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] A fundamental method of software analysis is disassembly.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] Unlike decompilers, which make attempts at recreating high-level human readable structures using binaries, disassemblers are aimed at generating a symbolic assembly, meaning it's attempting to reconstruct the assembly closest to its executions.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] Disassembled code is hence normally more accurate but also lower level and less abstract than decompiled code and thus it can be much more easily analyzed.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] Assembly language source code generally permits the use of constants and programmer comments.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] These are usually removed from the assembled machine code by the assembler.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] If so, a disassembler operating on the machine code would produce disassembly lacking these constants and comments; the disassembled output becomes more difficult for a human to interpret than the original annotated source code.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] Some disassemblers provide a built-in code commenting feature where the generated output is enriched with comments regarding called API functions or parameters of called functions.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] Some disassemblers make use of the symbolic debugging information present in object files such as ELF.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] For example, IDA allows the human user to make up mnemonic symbols for values or regions of code in an interactive session: human insight applied to the disassembly process often parallels human creativity in the code writing process.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] It is not always possible to distinguish executable code from data within a binary.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] While common executable formats, such as ELF and PE, separate code and data into distinct sections, flat binaries do not, making it unclear whether a given location contains executable instructions or non-executable data.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] This ambiguity might complicate the disassembly process.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] Additionally, CPUs often allow dynamic jumps computed at runtime, which makes it impossible to identify all possible locations in the binary that might be executed as instructions.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] On computer architectures with variable-width instructions, such as in many CISC architectures, more than one valid disassembly may exist for the same binary.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] Disassemblers also cannot handle code that changes during execution, as static analysis cannot account for runtime modifications.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] Encryption, packing, or obfuscation are often applied to computer programs, especially as part of digital rights management to deter reverse engineering and cracking.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] These techniques pose additional challenges for disassembly, as the code must first be unpacked or decrypted before meaningful analysis can begin.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] Disassembly can be performed statically or dynamically.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] **Static disassembly** analyzes the binary without executing it, which enables offline inspection.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] However, static disassembly may misinterpret some operations or obfuscation.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] While both are respectively powerful, modern disassemblers often combine both approaches to improve accuracy in more complex binaries.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] A disassembler can be either stand-alone or interactive.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] A stand-alone disassembler generates an assembly language file upon execution, which can then be examined.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] In contrast, an interactive disassembler immediately reflects any changes made by the user.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] For example, if the disassembler initially treats a section of the program as data rather than code, the user can specify it as code.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] The disassembled code will then be updated and displayed instantly, allowing the user to analyze it and make further changes during the same session.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] Any interactive debugger will include some way of viewing the disassembly of the program being debugged.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] Often, the same disassembly tool will be packaged as a standalone disassembler distributed along with the debugger.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] For example, objdump, part of GNU Binutils, is related to the interactive debugger gdb.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] A dynamic disassembler can be integrated into the output of an emulator or hypervisor to trace the real-time execution of machine instructions, displaying them line-by-line.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] In this setup, along with the disassembled machine code, the disassembler can show changes to registers, data, or other state elements (such as condition codes) caused by each instructions.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] This provides powerful debugging information for problem resolution.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] However, the output size can become quite large, particularly if the tracing is active throughout the entire execution of a program.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] These features were first introduced in the early 1970s by OLIVER as part of its CICS debugging product and are now incorporated into the XPEDITER product from Compuware.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] A **length disassembler**, also known as **length disassembler engine** (**LDE**), is a tool that, given a sequence of bytes (instructions), outputs the number of bytes taken by the parsed instruction.
[src:radare2-analysis/disassembler] Notable open source projects for the x86 architecture include ldisasm, Tiny x86 Length Disassembler and Extended Length Disassembler Engine for x86-64.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] A **hex** (short for hexadecimal), **binary**, or **byte editor** is software that allows for editing data as binary data.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] It is particularly useful for editing non-human-readable data of a file, but can be used for any data.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] Generally, a hex editor is a standalone program, and its user experience is similar to that of a text editor.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] A user can see and edit the raw and exact contents of a file, as opposed to the interpretation of the content that other, higher level application software may associate with the file format.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] For example, this could be the data bytes that represent an image instead of a graphical representation.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] Generally, data is grouped in 4 groups of 4 bytes or 2 groups of 8 bytes, followed by one group of 16 printable ASCII characters which correspond to each pair of hex values (each byte).
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] Non-printable ASCII characters are typically represented by a dot (".") in the ASCII field.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] A hex editor is sometimes used to fix data corruption problems.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] It can be useful to bypass application edit checks which may prevent correction of erroneous data.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] It has been used to "patch" executable programs (change or add a few instructions) as an alternative to recompilation.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] Program fixes for IBM mainframe systems are sometimes distributed as patches rather than distributing a complete copy of the affected program.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] Since the invention of computers and their different uses, a variety of file formats has been created.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] In some special circumstances it was convenient to be able to access the data as a series of raw digits.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] A program called SUPERZAP (AMASPZAP) was available for IBM OS/360 systems which could edit raw disk records and also understood the format of executable files.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] Pairs of hexadecimal digits (each pair can represent a byte) are the current standard, because the vast majority of machines and file formats in use today handle data in units or groups of 8-bit bytes.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] Hexadecimal and also octal are common because these digits allow one to see which bits in a byte are set.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] Depending on the data content, decimal or other numerical base instead of hexadecimal representation can support editing operations also using template systems and data inspectors.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] Some hex editors offer a template system that can present the sequence of bytes of a binary file in a structured way, covering part or all of the desired file format.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] Usually the GUI for a template is a separate tool window next to the main hex editor.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] Some cheat engine systems consist only of such a template GUI.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] Typically, a template is represented as a list of labeled text boxes, such that individual values of a file can be easily edited in the appropriate format (e.g., as string, color, or decimal number).
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] Without template support, it is necessary to find the right offset in a file where the value that is to be changed is stored.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] Also, raw hex editing may require conversion from hexadecimal to decimal, catering for byte order, or other data type conversion peculiarities.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] Templates can be stored as files, thereby exchanged by users, and are often shared publicly over the manufacturer's website.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] Most if not all hex editors define their own template file format; there is no trend to support a standard or even compatibility between the various formats out in the wild.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] Advanced hex editors have scripting systems that let the user create macro like functionality as a sequence of user interface commands for automating common tasks.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] This can be used for providing scripts that automatically patch files (e.g., game cheating, modding, or product fixes provided by community) or to write more complex/intelligent templates.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] Scripting languages vary widely, often being product specific languages resembling MS-DOS batch files, to systems that support fully-fledged scripting languages such as Lua or Python.
[src:radare2-analysis/hex-editor] A few select editors have a plugin system that allows to extend the GUI and add new functionality, usually loading dynamic link libraries written in a C-compatible language(Different operating systems adopt distinct dynamic link library formats: DLL for Windows, SO for Linux, and Dylib for macOS.).
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] In computer science, **program analysis** is the process of analyzing the behavior of computer programs regarding a property such as correctness, robustness, safety and liveness.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Program analysis focuses on two major areas: program optimization and program correctness.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] The first focuses on improving the program’s performance while reducing the resource usage while the latter focuses on ensuring that the program does what it is supposed to do.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Program analysis can be performed without executing the program (static program analysis), during runtime (dynamic program analysis) or in a combination of both.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] In the context of program correctness, static analysis can discover vulnerabilities during the development phase of the program.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] These vulnerabilities are easier to correct than the ones found during the testing phase since static analysis leads to the root of the vulnerability.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Due to many forms of static analysis being computationally undecidable, the mechanisms for performing it may not always terminate with the correct answer.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] This can result in either false negatives ("no problems found" when the code does in fact have issues) or false positives, or because they may never return an incorrect answer but may also never terminate.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Despite these limitations, static analysis can still be valuable: the first type of mechanism might reduce the number of vulnerabilities, while the second can sometimes provide strong assurance of the absence of certain classes of vulnerabilities.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Incorrect optimizations are highly undesirable.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] A third-party optimization tool may be implemented in such a way as to never produce an incorrect optimization, but also so that it can, in some situations, continue running indefinitely until it finds one (which may never happen).
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] In this case, the developer using the tool would have to stop the tool and avoid running the tool on that piece of code again (or possibly modify the code to avoid tripping up the tool).
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] However, there is also a third strategy that is sometimes applicable for languages that are not completely specified, such as C.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] An optimizing compiler is at liberty to generate code that does anything at runtime – even crashes – if it encounters source code whose semantics are unspecified by the language standard in use.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] The purpose of control-flow analysis is to obtain information about which functions can be called at various points during the execution of a program.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] The collected information is represented by a control-flow graph (CFG) where the nodes are instructions of the program and the edges represent the flow of control.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] By identifying code blocks and loops a CFG becomes a starting point for compiler-made optimizations.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Data-flow analysis is a technique designed to gather information about the values at each point of the program and how they change over time.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] This technique is often used by compilers to optimize the code.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] One of the most well known examples of data-flow analysis is taint checking, which consists of considering all variables that contain user-supplied data – which is considered "tainted", i.e. insecure – and preventing those variables from being used until they have been sanitized.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] This technique is often used to prevent SQL injection attacks.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Taint checking can be done statically or dynamically.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Abstract interpretation allows the extraction of information about a possible execution of a program without actually executing the program.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] This information can be used by compilers to look for possible optimizations or for certifying a program against certain classes of bugs.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Type systems associate types to programs that fulfill certain requirements.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Their purpose is to select a subset of programs of a language that are considered correct according to a property.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Type checking is used in programming to limit how programming objects are used and what can they do.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] This is done by the compiler or interpreter.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Type checking can also help prevent vulnerabilities by ensuring that a signed value isn't attributed to an unsigned variable.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Type checking can be done statically (at compile time), dynamically (at runtime) or a combination of both.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Static type information (either inferred, or explicitly provided by type annotations in the source code) can also be used to do optimizations, such as replacing boxed arrays with unboxed arrays.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Effect systems are formal systems designed to represent the effects that executing a function or method can have.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] An effect codifies what is being done and with what it is being done – usually referred to as *effect kind* and *effect region*, respectively.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Model checking refers to strict, formal, and automated ways to check if a *model* (which in this context means a formal model of a piece of code, though in other contexts it can be a model of a piece of hardware) complies with a given specification.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Due to the inherent finite-state nature of code, and both the specification and the code being convertible into logical formulae, it is possible to check if the system violates the specification using efficient algorithmic methods.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Dynamic analysis can use runtime knowledge of the program to increase the precision of the analysis, while also providing runtime protection, but it can only analyze a single execution of the problem and might degrade the program’s performance due to the runtime checks.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Software should be tested to ensure its quality and that it performs as it is supposed to in a reliable manner, and that it won’t create conflicts with other software that may function alongside it.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] The tests are performed by executing the program with an input and evaluating its behavior and the produced output.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Even if no security requirements are specified, additional security testing should be performed to ensure that an attacker can’t tamper with the software and steal information, disrupt the software’s normal operations, or use it as a pivot to attack its users.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Program monitoring records and logs different kinds of information about the program such as resource usage, events, and interactions, so that it can be reviewed to find or pinpoint causes of abnormal behavior.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Furthermore, it can be used to perform security audits.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Automated monitoring of programs is sometimes referred to as runtime verification.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] For a given subset of a program’s behavior, program slicing consists of reducing the program to the minimum form that still produces the selected behavior.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] The reduced program is called a “slice” and is a faithful representation of the original program within the domain of the specified behavior subset.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] Generally, finding a slice is an unsolvable problem, but by specifying the target behavior subset by the values of a set of variables, it is possible to obtain approximate slices using a data-flow algorithm.
[src:radare2-analysis/program-analysis] These slices are usually used by developers during debugging to locate the source of errors.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] Radare2 was created in February 2006, aiming to provide a free and simple command-line interface for a hexadecimal editor supporting 64 bit offsets to make searches and recovering data from hard-disks, for forensic purposes.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] Since then, the project has grown with the aim changed to provide a complete framework for analyzing binaries while adhering to several principles of the Unix philosophy.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] In 2009, the decision was made to completely rewrite it, to get around limitations in the initial design.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] Since then, the project continued to grow, and attracted several resident developers.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] In 2016, the first *r2con* took place in Barcelona, gathering more than 100 participants, featuring talks about various features and improvements of the framework.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] Radare2 has been the focus of multiple presentations at several high-profile security conferences, like the recon, hack.lu, 33c3.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] In 2020 Radare2 was forked as Rizin due to disagreements between the original author and a group of outside contributors.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] Radare2 itself has a steep learning curve since its main executable binaries are operated by a command line interface.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] Originally built around a hexadecimal editor, it now has a multitude of tools and features, and also bindings for several languages.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] Alongside the command line interface, it has a web user interface option and an official graphical user interface project called Iaito.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] Radare2 is able to assemble and disassemble a lot of software programs, mainly executables, but it can also perform binary diffing with graphs, extract information like relocations symbols, and various other types of data.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] Internally, it uses a NoSQL database named sdb to keep track of analysis information that can be inferred by Radare2 or manually added by the user.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] Since it is able to deal with malformed binaries, it has also been used by software security researchers for analysis purposes.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] Radare2 has a built-in debugger that is lower-level than GDB.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] It can also interface with GDB and WineDBG to debug Windows binaries on other systems.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] In addition, it can also be used as a kernel debugger with VMWare.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] Since it features a disassembler and a low-level debugger, Radare2 can be useful to developers of exploits.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] The software has features which assist in exploit development, such as a ROP gadget search engine and mitigation detection.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] Because of the software's flexibility and support for many file formats, it is often used by capture the flag teams and other security-oriented personnel.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] Radare2 can also assist in creating shellcodes with its 'ragg2' tool, similar to metasploit.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] Project Iaito has been developed as the first dedicated graphical user interface (GUI) for Radare2; it's been forked by Cutter as secondly developed graphical user interface (GUI) for Radare2.
[src:radare2-analysis/radare2] When the Cutter project was separated from Radare2 project at the end of 2020, Iaito was re-developed to be the current official Radare2 graphical user interface (GUI) maintained by Radare2 project members.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Although the process is specific to the object on which it is being performed, all reverse engineering processes consist of three basic steps: information extraction, modeling, and review.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Information extraction is the practice of gathering all relevant information for performing the operation.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Modeling is the practice of combining the gathered information into an abstract model, which can be used as a guide for designing the new object or system.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Review is the testing of the model to ensure the validity of the chosen abstract.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering is applicable in the fields of computer engineering, mechanical engineering, design, electrical and electronic engineering, civil engineering, nuclear engineering, aerospace engineering, software engineering, chemical engineering, systems biology and more.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] There are many reasons for performing reverse engineering in various fields.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering has its origins in the analysis of hardware for commercial or military advantage.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] However, the reverse engineering process may not always be concerned with creating a copy or changing the artifact in some way.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] It may be used as part of an analysis to deduce design features from products with little or no additional knowledge about the procedures involved in their original production.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] In some cases, the goal of the reverse engineering process can simply be a redocumentation of legacy systems.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Even when the reverse-engineered product is that of a competitor, the goal may not be to copy it but to perform competitor analysis.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Software reverse engineering can help to improve the understanding of the underlying source code for the maintenance and improvement of the software.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Relevant information can be extracted to make a decision for software development and graphical representations of the code can provide alternate views regarding the source code, which can help to detect and fix a software bug or vulnerability.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Frequently, as some software develops, its design information and improvements are often lost over time, but that lost information can usually be recovered with reverse engineering.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The process can also help to cut down the time required to understand the source code, thus reducing the overall cost of the software development.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering can also help to detect and to eliminate a malicious code written to the software with better code detectors.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reversing a source code can be used to find alternate uses of the source code, such as detecting the unauthorized replication of the source code where it was not intended to be used, or revealing how a competitor's product was built.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] That process is commonly used for "cracking" software and media to remove their copy protection, or to create a possibly improved copy or even a knockoff, which is usually the goal of a competitor or a hacker.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Malware developers often use reverse engineering techniques to find vulnerabilities in an operating system to build a computer virus that can exploit the system vulnerabilities.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering is also being used in cryptanalysis to find vulnerabilities in substitution cipher, symmetric-key algorithm or public-key cryptography.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] As computer-aided design (CAD) has become more popular, reverse engineering has become a viable method to create a 3D virtual model of an existing physical part for use in 3D CAD, CAM, CAE, or other software.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The reverse-engineering process involves measuring an object and then reconstructing it as a 3D model.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The physical object can be measured using 3D scanning technologies like CMMs, laser scanners, structured light digitizers, or industrial CT scanning (computed tomography).
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The measured data alone, usually represented as a point cloud, lacks topological information and design intent.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The former may be recovered by converting the point cloud to a triangular-faced mesh.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering aims to go beyond producing such a mesh and to recover the design intent in terms of simple analytical surfaces where appropriate (planes, cylinders, etc.) as well as possibly NURBS surfaces to produce a boundary-representation CAD model.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Recovery of such a model allows a design to be modified to meet new requirements, a manufacturing plan to be generated, etc.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Hybrid modeling is a commonly used term when NURBS and parametric modeling are implemented together.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Using a combination of geometric and freeform surfaces can provide a powerful method of 3D modeling.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Areas of freeform data can be combined with exact geometric surfaces to create a hybrid model.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] A typical example of this would be the reverse engineering of a cylinder head, which includes freeform cast features, such as water jackets and high-tolerance machined areas.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering is also used by businesses to bring existing physical geometry into digital product development environments, to make a digital 3D record of their own products, or to assess competitors' products.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] It is used to analyze how a product works, what it does, what components it has; estimate costs; identify potential patent infringement; etc.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Value engineering, a related activity that is also used by businesses, involves deconstructing and analyzing products.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] However, the objective is to find opportunities for cost-cutting.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering of printed circuit boards involves recreating fabrication data for a particular circuit board.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] This is done primarily to identify a design, and learn the functional and structural characteristics of a design.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] It also allows for the discovery of the design principles behind a product, especially if this design information is not easily available.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Outdated PCBs are often subject to reverse engineering, especially when they perform highly critical functions such as powering machinery, or other electronic components.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering these old parts can allow the reconstruction of the PCB if it performs some crucial task, as well as finding alternatives which provide the same function, or in upgrading the old PCB.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering PCBs largely follow the same series of steps.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] First, images are created by drawing, scanning, or taking photographs of the PCB.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Then, these images are ported to suitable reverse engineering software in order to create a rudimentary design for the new PCB.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The quality of these images that is necessary for suitable reverse engineering is proportional to the complexity of the PCB itself.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] More complicated PCBs require well lighted photos on dark backgrounds, while fairly simple PCBs can be recreated simply with just basic dimensioning.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Each layer of the PCB is carefully recreated in the software with the intent of producing a final design as close to the initial.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Then, the schematics for the circuit are finally generated using an appropriate tool.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering is a process of examination only, and the software system under consideration is not modified, which would otherwise be re-engineering or restructuring.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering can be performed from any stage of the product cycle, not necessarily from the functional end product.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] There are two components in reverse engineering: redocumentation and design recovery.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Redocumentation is the creation of new representation of the computer code so that it is easier to understand.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Meanwhile, design recovery is the use of deduction or reasoning from general knowledge or personal experience of the product to understand the product's functionality fully.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] It can also be seen as "going backwards through the development cycle".
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] In this model, the output of the implementation phase (in source code form) is reverse-engineered back to the analysis phase, in an inversion of the traditional waterfall model.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Another term for this technique is program comprehension.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The Working Conference on Reverse Engineering (WCRE) has been held yearly to explore and expand the techniques of reverse engineering.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Computer-aided software engineering (CASE) and automated code generation have contributed greatly in the field of reverse engineering.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Software anti-tamper technology like obfuscation is used to deter both reverse engineering and re-engineering of proprietary software and software-powered systems.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] In practice, two main types of reverse engineering emerge.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] In the first case, source code is already available for the software, but higher-level aspects of the program, which are perhaps poorly documented or documented but no longer valid, are discovered.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] In the second case, there is no source code available for the software, and any efforts towards discovering one possible source code for the software are regarded as reverse engineering.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The second usage of the term is more familiar to most people.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering of software can make use of the clean room design technique to avoid copyright infringement.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] On a related note, black box testing in software engineering has a lot in common with reverse engineering.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The tester usually has the API but has the goals to find bugs and undocumented features by bashing the product from outside.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Binary reverse engineering is performed if source code for a software is unavailable.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] This process is sometimes termed *reverse code engineering*, or RCE.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] For example, decompilation of binaries for the Java platform can be accomplished by using Jad.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] One famous case of reverse engineering was the first non-IBM implementation of the PC BIOS, which launched the historic IBM PC compatible industry that has been the overwhelmingly-dominant computer hardware platform for many years.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering of software is protected in the US by the fair use exception in copyright law.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The Wine project does the same thing for the Windows API, and OpenOffice.org is one party doing that for the Microsoft Office file formats.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering of software can be accomplished by various methods.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Disassembly using a disassembler, meaning the raw machine language of the program is read and understood in its own terms, only with the aid of machine-language mnemonics.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] It works on any computer program but can take quite some time, especially for those who are not used to machine code.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The Interactive Disassembler is a particularly popular tool.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Decompilation using a decompiler, a process that tries, with varying results, to recreate the source code in some high-level language for a program only available in machine code or bytecode.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Software classification is the process of identifying similarities between different software binaries (such as two different versions of the same binary) used to detect code relations between software samples.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The task was traditionally done manually for several reasons (such as patch analysis for vulnerability detection and copyright infringement), but it can now be done somewhat automatically for large numbers of samples.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] This method is being used mostly for long and thorough reverse engineering tasks (complete analysis of a complex algorithm or big piece of software).
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] In general, statistical classification is considered to be a hard problem, which is also true for software classification, and so few solutions/tools that handle this task well.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] A number of UML tools refer to the process of importing and analysing source code to generate UML diagrams as "reverse engineering" .
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Although UML is one approach in providing "reverse engineering" more recent advances in international standards activities have resulted in the development of the Knowledge Discovery Metamodel (KDM).
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The standard delivers an ontology for the intermediate (or abstracted) representation of programming language constructs and their interrelationships.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] An Object Management Group standard (on its way to becoming an ISO standard as well), KDM has started to take hold in industry with the development of tools and analysis environments that can deliver the extraction and analysis of source, binary, and byte code.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] For source code analysis, KDM's granular standards' architecture enables the extraction of software system flows (data, control, and call maps), architectures, and business layer knowledge (rules, terms, and process).
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The standard enables the use of a common data format (XMI) enabling the correlation of the various layers of system knowledge for either detailed analysis (such as root cause, impact) or derived analysis (such as business process extraction).
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Although efforts to represent language constructs can be never-ending because of the number of languages, the continuous evolution of software languages, and the development of new languages, the standard does allow for the use of extensions to support the broad language set as well as evolution.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] KDM is compatible with UML, BPMN, RDF, and other standards enabling migration into other environments and thus leverage system knowledge for efforts such as software system transformation and enterprise business layer analysis.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Protocols are sets of rules that describe message formats and how messages are exchanged: the protocol state machine.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Accordingly, the problem of protocol reverse-engineering can be partitioned into two subproblems: message format and state-machine reverse-engineering.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The message formats have traditionally been reverse-engineered by a tedious manual process, which involved analysis of how protocol implementations process messages, but recent research proposed a number of automatic solutions.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Typically, the automatic approaches group observe messages into clusters by using various clustering analyses, or they emulate the protocol implementation tracing the message processing.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] There has been less work on reverse-engineering of state-machines of protocols.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] In general, offline learning of small state-machines is known to be NP-complete, but online learning can be done in polynomial time.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] An automatic offline approach has been demonstrated by Comparetti et al. and an online approach by Cho et al.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Other components of typical protocols, like encryption and hash functions, can be reverse-engineered automatically as well.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Typically, the automatic approaches trace the execution of protocol implementations and try to detect buffers in memory holding unencrypted packets.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering is an invasive and destructive form of analyzing a smart card.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The attacker uses chemicals to etch away layer after layer of the smart card and takes pictures with a scanning electron microscope (SEM).
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] That technique can reveal the complete hardware and software part of the smart card.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The major problem for the attacker is to bring everything into the right order to find out how everything works.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The makers of the card try to hide keys and operations by mixing up memory positions, such as by bus scrambling.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] In some cases, it is even possible to attach a probe to measure voltages while the smart card is still operational.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The makers of the card employ sensors to detect and prevent that attack.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] That attack is not very common because it requires both a large investment in effort and special equipment that is generally available only to large chip manufacturers.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Furthermore, the payoff from this attack is low since other security techniques are often used such as shadow accounts.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] It is still uncertain whether attacks against chip-and-PIN cards to replicate encryption data and then to crack PINs would provide a cost-effective attack on multifactor authentication.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Full reverse engineering proceeds in several major steps.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] The first step after images have been taken with a SEM is stitching the images together, which is necessary because each layer cannot be captured by a single shot.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] A SEM needs to sweep across the area of the circuit and take several hundred images to cover the entire layer.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Image stitching takes as input several hundred pictures and outputs a single properly overlapped picture of the complete layer.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Next, the stitched layers need to be aligned because the sample, after etching, cannot be put into the exact same position relative to the SEM each time.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Therefore, the stitched versions will not overlap in the correct fashion, as on the real circuit.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Usually, three corresponding points are selected, and a transformation applied on the basis of that.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] To extract the circuit structure, the aligned, stitched images need to be segmented, which highlights the important circuitry and separates it from the uninteresting background and insulating materials.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Finally, the wires can be traced from one layer to the next, and the netlist of the circuit, which contains all of the circuit's information, can be reconstructed.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering is often used by people to copy other nations' technologies, devices, or information that have been obtained by regular troops in the fields or by intelligence operations.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] It was often used during the Second World War and the Cold War.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering concepts have been applied to biology as well, specifically to the task of understanding the structure and function of gene regulatory networks.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] They regulate almost every aspect of biological behavior and allow cells to carry out physiological processes and responses to perturbations.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Understanding the structure and the dynamic behavior of gene networks is therefore one of the paramount challenges of systems biology, with immediate practical repercussions in several applications that are beyond basic research.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] There are several methods for reverse engineering gene regulatory networks by using molecular biology and data science methods.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Often, gene network reliability is tested by genetic perturbation experiments followed by dynamic modelling, based on the principle that removing one network node has predictable effects on the functioning of the remaining nodes of the network.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Applications of the reverse engineering of gene networks range from understanding mechanisms of plant physiology to the highlighting of new targets for anticancer therapy.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering applies primarily to gaining understanding of a process or artifact in which the manner of its construction, use, or internal processes has not been made clear by its creator.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Patented items do not of themselves have to be reverse-engineered to be studied, for the essence of a patent is that inventors provide a detailed public disclosure themselves, and in return receive legal protection of the invention that is involved.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] However, an item produced under one or more patents could also include other technology that is not patented and not disclosed.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Indeed, one common motivation of reverse engineering is to determine whether a competitor's product contains patent infringement or copyright infringement.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] In the United States, even if an artifact or process is protected by trade secrets, reverse-engineering the artifact or process is often lawful if it has been legitimately obtained.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Legal analysis has shown that reverse engineering may qualify as fair use when the intent is to study how a system functions, or conduct security research, assuming the copyright property is not redistributed Court rulings such as *Sega Enterprises Ltd. v.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Accolade, Inc.* have further clarified that reverse engineering to gain access to unprotected functional elements of software can be lawful under U.S. copyright doctrine.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] Reverse engineering of computer software often falls under both contract law as a breach of contract as well as any other relevant laws.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] That is because most end-user license agreements specifically prohibit it, and US courts have ruled that if such terms are present, they override the copyright law that expressly permits it (see *Bowers v.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] A limited exemption exists that allows the knowledge thus gained to be shared and used for interoperability purposes.
[src:radare2-analysis/reverse-engineering] EU Directive 2009/24 on the legal protection of computer programs, which superseded an earlier (1991) directive, governs reverse engineering in countries of the European Union.
